 to distinguish them from non-Jews. Coupled with the failure to formulate a viable alternative national identity (either "Hebrew" or "Israeli"), it leads the ostensibly secular state to apply a narrow interpretation of Jewish religion as a political tool for maintaining a Jewish majority.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aJewsxIdentityxHistory. 0aJewsxPolitics and government. 0aJewszIsraelxIdentityxHistory. 0aNational characteristics, Israeli. 0aSovereignty. 0aZionism and Judaism. 0aZionism. 4aArea Studies : Israel Studies. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion and Politics. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2017z978311149102840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438465357423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438465357/original  a978-3-11-149102-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles